 Using a utility under risk, we explore how varied risk-attitudes could
 result in long-term differences under rising and declining phases of economic
 growth.
 The role of taxation policies in status consumption as risky allocations
 is also discussed.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The studies on conspicuous consumption have recently explored visible consumptio
n in the developing economies.
 As a specific instance of status consumption, visible consumption is assumed
 to occur through a certain type of (visible) goods that are futile for
 the consumer.
 The assumption permits the separability of demand for visible goods from
 non-visible goods in the empirically analyses - where the separation between
 visible and non-visible goods is arrived at with independent surveys.
 Instead of using an approach that relies on such a survey of visible items
 we review what status consumption would mean in the context of wealth differenc
es and social stratification - whose effects may not be captured by a simple
 selection of visible items in a developing economy.
 In thus restating status consumption, we bank upon the first explorations
 in status consumption where it has been identified as a way for the consumer
 to offset the existing wealth or income differences
